If you’ve never had the pleasure of an RPSI railtour, add it to your bucket list. Like everyone else they’ve had a tough couple of years and every ticket sold helps to keep main line steam operation alive north & south of the border. https://t.co/NB3gSxELew

For example, on day 1 of a 2-day trip to Cork with GNR(I) No. 85, we drank it dry (as a lightweight I played only a small part) & the RPSI crew had to buy supplies from a bar over the road from Cork stn. We drained the last pints of that on as we coasted back into Dublin on day 2

Over several trips I’ve learned more about Irish railway history (and Ireland) from conversations with people in that coach than from years of studying, although I have to admit that I can’t remember as much of it as I’d like…

Say hello to @RPSITrains @SteamTrains_Dub Cravens Bar Car - the only one in the world serving (a very fine pint of) draught #Guinness. A wonderful place to spend a day with some of the friendliest & most knowledgeable railway people you’ll ever meet. (1/2) https://t.co/ZmZge7iemv

So, to sum up, there’s no doubt #Stocksbridge needs fast, reliable rail link to #Sheffield but doing it properly requires careful planning and probably more £££ than @transportgovuk is expecting to spend. It’s far more complicated than #Okehampton & could be useless if bodged.

…it is connected to the existing @SCSupertram network through #Sheffield city centre & out to Meadowhall/Rotherham. No easy options making that link either though! GCR & Supertram lines are close together at Bernard Rd but at different heights.

However you solve this problem, it all adds to the journey time & at the end of it you’re still at #Sheffield station, some way out of the city centre, which means that buses save a long walk & will remain competitive for many. Tram-Train helps to overcome this if…

The ex-GCR line through Vic faces E to W & the MR route runs N to S at a considerably lower level, so getting from one to the other is ‘tricky’. For a while in the early-‘80s, BR Sheffield-Hudds DMUs reversed at Nunnery Jn to access the GCR, but that’s unlikely to be accepted now

Except that buses go right into the city centre & Sheffield’s rail stations are not conveniently sited if you’re going into town for work/study or shopping. Our route runs through the old Sheff Victoria (closed 1970) and there’s no direct connection to #Sheffield Midland.

…there’s a bus direct into #Sheffield city centre every couple of minutes (primary reason why the local train services were cut & stns between Sheffield and Penistone closed in 1959). No doubt trams/trains will be quicker into town than buses, especially when the A61 is jammed…

We continue through Beeley Woods, past the old Batchelor’s Mushy Pea factory (no, really) to Wadsley Bridge, which remained open for football specials until 1991 but has since been steadily destroyed. It’s right on the A61, close to shopping centres & an ideal  interchange, but..

…we run through the woods along the opposite side of the valley to all habitation until we reach Oughtibridge (or Oughty Bridge if you’re of GCR persuasion). Although new housing estates have expanded the village towards the old station, the location is still far from ideal.

The SLR meets @networkrail at Deepcar, where there used to be exchange sidings with the Woodhead Route. Deepcar stn is now a private house and way out of the village centre - neither use nor ornament in terms of attracting passengers. Continuing east…

Tram-Train would seem to be the obvious solution, running off an upgraded SLR to serve Fox Valley shopping centre and the middle of #Stocksbridge town centre. So far, so good. What about the rest of the route?

Let’s take a journey into town by rail. Our trip starts in the middle of an operational steelworks on the #Stocksbridge Light Rly, which has never been anything other than an industrial line (fascinating story in itself, but another time maybe).
